{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646317"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:28:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:28:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18173"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18173"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10887"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79220"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10887"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18173"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64572"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27123"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79220"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a variety of joint types in the vertebral column.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following joint types allows the cranium and C1 to rotate on C2?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atlanto-axial joints","Symphysis-type joints","Synovial joints","Occipital-atlantal joints","Sacro-iliac joints"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eatlanto-axial joints\u003C/strong\u003E are responsible for the rotation of the head. These are synovial joints located between the first cervical vertebra (C1, also known as the atlas) and the second cervical vertebra (C2, also known as the axis). The dens of the axis acts as a pivot that allows the atlas and attached skull to rotate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital-atlantal joints\u003C/strong\u003E are located between the occipital bone of the skull and the atlas (C1). These joints primarily allow for nodding movements of the head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacro-iliac joints\u003C/strong\u003E are located in the pelvis and do not contribute to neck movement. They are involved in weight transfer from the upper body to the lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynovial joints\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad category that includes many types of joints, including the atlanto-axial joint. However, the question specifically asks for the joint type that allows rotation between C1 and C2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESymphysis-type joints\u003C/strong\u003E are cartilaginous joints found in areas such as the pubic symphysis and intervertebral discs, and they do not allow for the type of rotation described in the question.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The atlanto-axial joint is a pivotal synovial joint that allows rotation of the head.","The cervical spine includes various joint types, but the atlanto-axial joint is specifically responsible for head rotation."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64572"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18173"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64572"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T20:26:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T20:27:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10887"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79220"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags